Aet I. Scene ii. Hegio, dressed in white (the colour worn by old men in Comedy), comes out of his house accompanied by the overseer of the slaves, who is carrying two light sets of setters. Going up to the two Captives, he gives orders that they be put in the new fetters with liberty to walk about. As he turns to go away (V. 126), Ergasilus attracts his attention, and the two hold a conversation, in the course of which (V. 167) Hegio announces his plan 01· exchanging Tyndarus (1.0. the pretended Philocrates) for Philopolemus. After giving Ergasilus an invitation to dinner, Hegio goes back into the house.
